ARCHITECTURE.md
     1→# Architecture
     2→
     3→> Document is a work in progress!
     4→
     5→⌘K is born from a simple constraint: can you write a combobox with filtering and sorting using the [compound component](https://kentcdodds.com/blog/compound-components-with-react-hooks) approach? We didn't want to render items manually from an array:
     6→
     7→```tsx
     8→// No
     9→<>
    10→  {items.map((item) => {
    11→    return <div>{item}</div>
    12→  })}
    13→</>
    14→```
    15→
    16→We didn't want to provide a render prop:
    17→
    18→```tsx
    19→// No
    20→onItemRender={({ item }) => {
    21→  return <div>{item}</div>
    22→}}
    23→```
    24→
    25→Instead, we wanted to render components:
    26→
    27→```tsx
    28→// Yes
    29→<Item>My item</Item>
    30→```
    31→
    32→Especially, we wanted full component composition:
    33→
    34→```tsx
    35→// YES
    36→<>
    37→  <BlogItems />
    38→  {staticItems}
    39→</>
    40→```
    41→
    42→Compound components are natural and easy to write. A few months after exploring this library, we were pleased to see [Radix UI](https://www.radix-ui.com) released using this exact approach of component structure – setting the standard for ease of use and composability.
    43→
    44→However, for a combobox, it is a terrible, terrible constraint that we've spent 2 years fighting.
    45→
    46→## Approach
    47→
    48→⌘K always keeps every item and group rendered in the React tree. Each item and group adds or removes itself from the DOM based on the search input. The DOM is authoritative. Item selection order is based on the DOM order, which is based on the React render order, which the consumer provides.
    49→
    50→### Discarded approach
    51→
    52→We did not use `React.Children` iteration because it will not support component composition. There is no way to "peek inside" the items contained within `<BlogItems />`, so those items cannot be filtered.
    53→
    54→We did not use an object-based data array for each item, like `{ name: "Logout", action: () => logout() }` because this is strict and limiting. In reality, the interface of those objects grows with edge-cases, like `image`, `detailedSubTitle`, `hideWhenRootSearch`, etc. We prefer that you have full control of item rendering, including icons, keyboard shortcuts, and styling. Don't want an item shown? Don't render it. Only want to show an item under condition xyz? Render it.
    55→
    56→We did not use a render prop because they are an inelegant pattern and quickly fall to long, centralised if-else logic chains. For example, if you want a fancy sparkle rainbow item, you need a new if statement to render that item specially.
    57→
    58→The original approach for tracking which item was selected was to keep an index 0..n. But it's impossible to know which Item is in which position within the React tree when React Strict Mode is enabled, because `useEffect` runs twice and `useRef` cannot be used for stable IDs. <sup>This may be possible with `useId`, now.</sup> We created [use-descendants](https://github.com/pacocoursey/use-descendants) to track relative component indeces, but abandoned it because it could not work in Strict Mode, and will be incompatible with upcoming concurrent mode. Now, we track the selected item with its value, because it is stable across item mounts and unmounts.
    59→
    60→## Example
    61→
    62→```tsx
    63→<Input value="b" />
    64→<List>
    65→  <Item>A</Item>
    66→  <Item>B</Item>
    67→</List>
    68→```
    69→
    70→The "A" item should not be shown! But we cannot remove it from the React tree, because the user controls it. In most cases, this is easy because the rendered items is sourced from a backing data array:
    71→
    72→```tsx
    73→<>
    74→  {['A', 'B'].map((item) => {
    75→    if (matches(item, search)) {
    76→      return <Item>{item}</Item>
    77→    }
    78→  })}
    79→</>
    80→```
    81→
    82→But in our case, the item will remain in the React tree and just be removed from the DOM:
    83→
    84→```tsx
    85→<List>
    86→  {/* returns `null`, no DOM created */}
    87→  <Item>A</Item>
    88→  <Item>B</Item>
    89→</List>
    90→```
    91→
    92→## Performance
    93→
    94→This is more expensive memory wise, because if there are 2,000 items but the list is filtered to only 2 items, we still allocate memory for 2,000 instances of the Item component. But it's our only option! Thankfully we can still keep the DOM size to 2 items.
    95→
    96→## Groups
    97→
    98→Item mount informs both the root and the parent group, which keeps track of items within it. Each group informs the root.
LICENSE.md
README.md
     5→# ⌘K [![cmdk minzip package size](https://img.shields.io/bundlephobia/minzip/cmdk)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/cmdk?activeTab=code) [![cmdk package version](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/cmdk.svg?colorB=green)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/cmdk)
     6→
     7→⌘K is a command menu React component that can also be used as an accessible combobox. You render items, it filters and sorts them automatically. ⌘K supports a fully composable API <sup><sup>[How?](/ARCHITECTURE.md)</sup></sup>, so you can wrap items in other components or even as static JSX.
     8→
     9→## Install
    10→
    11→```bash
    12→pnpm install cmdk
    13→```
    14→
    15→## Use
    16→
    17→```tsx
    18→import { Command } from 'cmdk'
    19→
    20→const CommandMenu = () => {
    21→  return (
    22→    <Command label="Command Menu">
    23→      <Command.Input />
    24→      <Command.List>
    25→        <Command.Empty>No results found.</Command.Empty>
    26→
    27→        <Command.Group heading="Letters">
    28→          <Command.Item>a</Command.Item>
    29→          <Command.Item>b</Command.Item>
    30→          <Command.Separator />
    31→          <Command.Item>c</Command.Item>
    32→        </Command.Group>
    33→
    34→        <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
    35→      </Command.List>
    36→    </Command>
    37→  )
    38→}
    39→```
    40→
    41→Or in a dialog:
    42→
    43→```tsx
    44→import { Command } from 'cmdk'
    45→
    46→const CommandMenu = () => {
    47→  const [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
    48→
    49→  // Toggle the menu when ⌘K is pressed
    50→  React.useEffect(() => {
    51→    const down = (e) => {
    52→      if (e.key === 'k' && (e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey)) {
    53→        e.preventDefault()
    54→        setOpen((open) => !open)
    55→      }
    56→    }
    57→
    58→    document.addEventListener('keydown', down)
    59→    return () => document.removeEventListener('keydown', down)
    60→  }, [])
    61→
    62→  return (
    63→    <Command.Dialog open={open} onOpenChange={setOpen} label="Global Command Menu">
    64→      <Command.Input />
    65→      <Command.List>
    66→        <Command.Empty>No results found.</Command.Empty>
    67→
    68→        <Command.Group heading="Letters">
    69→          <Command.Item>a</Command.Item>
    70→          <Command.Item>b</Command.Item>
    71→          <Command.Separator />
    72→          <Command.Item>c</Command.Item>
    73→        </Command.Group>
    74→
    75→        <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
    76→      </Command.List>
    77→    </Command.Dialog>
    78→  )
    79→}
    80→```
    81→
    82→## Parts and styling
    83→
    84→All parts forward props, including `ref`, to an appropriate element. Each part has a specific data-attribute (starting with `cmdk-`) that can be used for styling.
    85→
    86→### Command `[cmdk-root]`
    87→
    88→Render this to show the command menu inline, or use [Dialog](#dialog-cmdk-dialog-cmdk-overlay) to render in a elevated context. Can be controlled with the `value` and `onValueChange` props.
    89→
    90→> **Note**
    91→>
    92→> Values are always trimmed with the [trim()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/trim) method.
    93→
    94→```tsx
    95→const [value, setValue] = React.useState('apple')
    96→
    97→return (
    98→  <Command value={value} onValueChange={setValue}>
    99→    <Command.Input />
   100→    <Command.List>
   101→      <Command.Item>Orange</Command.Item>
   102→      <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
   103→    </Command.List>
   104→  </Command>
   105→)
   106→```
   107→
   108→You can provide a custom `filter` function that is called to rank each item. Note that the value will be trimmed.
   109→
   110→```tsx
   111→<Command
   112→  filter={(value, search) => {
   113→    if (value.includes(search)) return 1
   114→    return 0
   115→  }}
   116→/>
   117→```
   118→
   119→A third argument, `keywords`, can also be provided to the filter function. Keywords act as aliases for the item value, and can also affect the rank of the item. Keywords are trimmed.
   120→
   121→```tsx
   122→<Command
   123→  filter={(value, search, keywords) => {
   124→    const extendValue = value + ' ' + keywords.join(' ')
   125→    if (extendValue.includes(search)) return 1
   126→    return 0
   127→  }}
   128→/>
   129→```
   130→
   131→Or disable filtering and sorting entirely:
   132→
   133→```tsx
   134→<Command shouldFilter={false}>
   135→  <Command.List>
   136→    {filteredItems.map((item) => {
   137→      return (
   138→        <Command.Item key={item} value={item}>
   139→          {item}
   140→        </Command.Item>
   141→      )
   142→    })}
   143→  </Command.List>
   144→</Command>
   145→```
   146→
   147→You can make the arrow keys wrap around the list (when you reach the end, it goes back to the first item) by setting the `loop` prop:
   148→
   149→```tsx
   150→<Command loop />
   151→```
   152→
   153→### Dialog `[cmdk-dialog]` `[cmdk-overlay]`
   154→
   155→Props are forwarded to [Command](#command-cmdk-root). Composes Radix UI's Dialog component. The overlay is always rendered. See the [Radix Documentation](https://www.radix-ui.com/docs/primitives/components/dialog) for more information. Can be controlled with the `open` and `onOpenChange` props.
   156→
   157→```tsx
   158→const [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
   159→
   160→return (
   161→  <Command.Dialog open={open} onOpenChange={setOpen}>
   162→    ...
   163→  </Command.Dialog>
   164→)
   165→```
   166→
   167→You can provide a `container` prop that accepts an HTML element that is forwarded to Radix UI's Dialog Portal component to specify which element the Dialog should portal into (defaults to `body`). See the [Radix Documentation](https://www.radix-ui.com/docs/primitives/components/dialog#portal) for more information.
   168→
   169→```tsx
   170→const containerElement = React.useRef(null)
   171→
   172→return (
   173→  <>
   174→    <Command.Dialog container={containerElement.current} />
   175→    <div ref={containerElement} />
   176→  </>
   177→)
   178→```
   179→
   180→### Input `[cmdk-input]`
   181→
   182→All props are forwarded to the underlying `input` element. Can be controlled with the `value` and `onValueChange` props.
   183→
   184→```tsx
   185→const [search, setSearch] = React.useState('')
   186→
   187→return <Command.Input value={search} onValueChange={setSearch} />
   188→```
   189→
   190→### List `[cmdk-list]`
   191→
   192→Contains items and groups. Animate height using the `--cmdk-list-height` CSS variable.
   193→
   194→```css
   195→[cmdk-list] {
   196→  min-height: 300px;
   197→  height: var(--cmdk-list-height);
   198→  max-height: 500px;
   199→  transition: height 100ms ease;
   200→}
   201→```
   202→
   203→To scroll item into view earlier near the edges of the viewport, use scroll-padding:
   204→
   205→```css
   206→[cmdk-list] {
   207→  scroll-padding-block-start: 8px;
   208→  scroll-padding-block-end: 8px;
   209→}
   210→```
   211→
   212→### Item `[cmdk-item]` `[data-disabled?]` `[data-selected?]`
   213→
   214→Item that becomes active on pointer enter. You should provide a unique `value` for each item, but it will be automatically inferred from the `.textContent`.
   215→
   216→```tsx
   217→<Command.Item
   218→  onSelect={(value) => console.log('Selected', value)}
   219→  // Value is implicity "apple" because of the provided text content
   220→>
   221→  Apple
   222→</Command.Item>
   223→```
   224→
   225→You can also provide a `keywords` prop to help with filtering. Keywords are trimmed.
   226→
   227→```tsx
   228→<Command.Item keywords={['fruit', 'apple']}>Apple</Command.Item>
   229→```
   230→
   231→```tsx
   232→<Command.Item
   233→  onSelect={(value) => console.log('Selected', value)}
   234→  // Value is implicity "apple" because of the provided text content
   235→>
   236→  Apple
   237→</Command.Item>
   238→```
   239→
   240→You can force an item to always render, regardless of filtering, by passing the `forceMount` prop.
   241→
   242→### Group `[cmdk-group]` `[hidden?]`
   243→
   244→Groups items together with the given `heading` (`[cmdk-group-heading]`).
   245→
   246→```tsx
   247→<Command.Group heading="Fruit">
   248→  <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
   249→</Command.Group>
   250→```
   251→
   252→Groups will not unmount from the DOM, rather the `hidden` attribute is applied to hide it from view. This may be relevant in your styling.
   253→
   254→You can force a group to always render, regardless of filtering, by passing the `forceMount` prop.
   255→
   256→### Separator `[cmdk-separator]`
   257→
   258→Visible when the search query is empty or `alwaysRender` is true, hidden otherwise.
   259→
   260→### Empty `[cmdk-empty]`
   261→
   262→Automatically renders when there are no results for the search query.
   263→
   264→### Loading `[cmdk-loading]`
   265→
   266→You should conditionally render this with `progress` while loading asynchronous items.
   267→
   268→```tsx
   269→const [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(false)
   270→
   271→return <Command.List>{loading && <Command.Loading>Hang on…</Command.Loading>}</Command.List>
   272→```
   273→
   274→### `useCommandState(state => state.selectedField)`
   275→
   276→Hook that composes [`useSyncExternalStore`](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore). Pass a function that returns a slice of the command menu state to re-render when that slice changes. This hook is provided for advanced use cases and should not be commonly used.
   277→
   278→A good use case would be to render a more detailed empty state, like so:
   279→
   280→```tsx
   281→const search = useCommandState((state) => state.search)
   282→return <Command.Empty>No results found for "{search}".</Command.Empty>
   283→```
   284→
   285→## Examples
   286→
   287→Code snippets for common use cases.
   288→
   289→### Nested items
   290→
   291→Often selecting one item should navigate deeper, with a more refined set of items. For example selecting "Change theme…" should show new items "Dark theme" and "Light theme". We call these sets of items "pages", and they can be implemented with simple state:
   292→
   293→```tsx
   294→const ref = React.useRef(null)
   295→const [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
   296→const [search, setSearch] = React.useState('')
   297→const [pages, setPages] = React.useState([])
   298→const page = pages[pages.length - 1]
   299→
   300→return (
   301→  <Command
   302→    onKeyDown={(e) => {
   303→      // Escape goes to previous page
   304→      // Backspace goes to previous page when search is empty
   305→      if (e.key === 'Escape' || (e.key === 'Backspace' && !search)) {
   306→        e.preventDefault()
   307→        setPages((pages) => pages.slice(0, -1))
   308→      }
   309→    }}
   310→  >
   311→    <Command.Input value={search} onValueChange={setSearch} />
   312→    <Command.List>
   313→      {!page && (
   314→        <>
   315→          <Command.Item onSelect={() => setPages([...pages, 'projects'])}>Search projects…</Command.Item>
   316→          <Command.Item onSelect={() => setPages([...pages, 'teams'])}>Join a team…</Command.Item>
   317→        </>
   318→      )}
   319→
   320→      {page === 'projects' && (
   321→        <>
   322→          <Command.Item>Project A</Command.Item>
   323→          <Command.Item>Project B</Command.Item>
   324→        </>
   325→      )}
   326→
   327→      {page === 'teams' && (
   328→        <>
   329→          <Command.Item>Team 1</Command.Item>
   330→          <Command.Item>Team 2</Command.Item>
   331→        </>
   332→      )}
   333→    </Command.List>
   334→  </Command>
   335→)
   336→```
   337→
   338→### Show sub-items when searching
   339→
   340→If your items have nested sub-items that you only want to reveal when searching, render based on the search state:
   341→
   342→```tsx
   343→const SubItem = (props) => {
   344→  const search = useCommandState((state) => state.search)
   345→  if (!search) return null
   346→  return <Command.Item {...props} />
   347→}
   348→
   349→return (
   350→  <Command>
   351→    <Command.Input />
   352→    <Command.List>
   353→      <Command.Item>Change theme…</Command.Item>
   354→      <SubItem>Change theme to dark</SubItem>
   355→      <SubItem>Change theme to light</SubItem>
   356→    </Command.List>
   357→  </Command>
   358→)
   359→```
   360→
   361→### Asynchronous results
   362→
   363→Render the items as they become available. Filtering and sorting will happen automatically.
   364→
   365→```tsx
   366→const [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(false)
   367→const [items, setItems] = React.useState([])
   368→
   369→React.useEffect(() => {
   370→  async function getItems() {
   371→    setLoading(true)
   372→    const res = await api.get('/dictionary')
   373→    setItems(res)
   374→    setLoading(false)
   375→  }
   376→
   377→  getItems()
   378→}, [])
   379→
   380→return (
   381→  <Command>
   382→    <Command.Input />
   383→    <Command.List>
   384→      {loading && <Command.Loading>Fetching words…</Command.Loading>}
   385→      {items.map((item) => {
   386→        return (
   387→          <Command.Item key={`word-${item}`} value={item}>
   388→            {item}
   389→          </Command.Item>
   390→        )
   391→      })}
   392→    </Command.List>
   393→  </Command>
   394→)
   395→```
   396→
   397→### Use inside Popover
   398→
   399→We recommend using the [Radix UI popover](https://www.radix-ui.com/docs/primitives/components/popover) component. ⌘K relies on the Radix UI Dialog component, so this will reduce your bundle size a bit due to shared dependencies.
   400→
   401→```bash
   402→$ pnpm install @radix-ui/react-popover
   403→```
   404→
   405→Render `Command` inside of the popover content:
   406→
   407→```tsx
   408→import * as Popover from '@radix-ui/react-popover'
   409→
   410→return (
   411→  <Popover.Root>
   412→    <Popover.Trigger>Toggle popover</Popover.Trigger>
   413→
   414→    <Popover.Content>
   415→      <Command>
   416→        <Command.Input />
   417→        <Command.List>
   418→          <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
   419→        </Command.List>
   420→      </Command>
   421→    </Popover.Content>
   422→  </Popover.Root>
   423→)
   424→```
   425→
   426→### Drop in stylesheets
   427→
   428→You can find global stylesheets to drop in as a starting point for styling. See [website/styles/cmdk](website/styles/cmdk) for examples.
   429→
   430→## FAQ
   431→
   432→**Accessible?** Yes. Labeling, aria attributes, and DOM ordering tested with Voice Over and Chrome DevTools. [Dialog](#dialog-cmdk-dialog-cmdk-overlay) composes an accessible Dialog implementation.
   433→
   434→**Virtualization?** No. Good performance up to 2,000-3,000 items, though. Read below to bring your own.
   435→
   436→**Filter/sort items manually?** Yes. Pass `shouldFilter={false}` to [Command](#command-cmdk-root). Better memory usage and performance. Bring your own virtualization this way.
   437→
   438→**React 18 safe?** Yes, required. Uses React 18 hooks like `useId` and `useSyncExternalStore`.
   439→
   440→**Unstyled?** Yes, use the listed CSS selectors.
   441→
   442→**Hydration mismatch?** No, likely a bug in your code. Ensure the `open` prop to `Command.Dialog` is `false` on the server.
   443→
   444→**React strict mode safe?** Yes. Open an issue if you notice an issue.
   445→
   446→**Weird/wrong behavior?** Make sure your `Command.Item` has a `key` and unique `value`.
   447→
   448→**Concurrent mode safe?** Maybe, but concurrent mode is not yet real. Uses risky approaches like manual DOM ordering.
   449→
   450→**React server component?** No, it's a client component.
   451→
   452→**Listen for ⌘K automatically?** No, do it yourself to have full control over keybind context.
   453→
   454→**React Native?** No, and no plans to support it. If you build a React Native version, let us know and we'll link your repository here.
   455→
   456→## History
   457→
   458→Written in 2019 by Paco ([@pacocoursey](https://twitter.com/pacocoursey)) to see if a composable combobox API was possible. Used for the Vercel command menu and autocomplete by Rauno ([@raunofreiberg](https://twitter.com/raunofreiberg)) in 2020. Re-written independently in 2022 with a simpler and more performant approach. Ideas and help from Shu ([@shuding\_](https://twitter.com/shuding_)).
   459→
   460→[use-descendants](https://github.com/pacocoursey/use-descendants) was extracted from the 2019 version.
   461→
   462→## Testing
   463→
   464→First, install dependencies and Playwright browsers:
   465→
   466→```bash
   467→pnpm install
   468→pnpm playwright install
   469→```
   470→
   471→Then ensure you've built the library:
   472→
   473→```bash
   474→pnpm build
   475→```
   476→
   477→Then run the tests using your local build against real browser engines:
   478→
   479→```bash
   480→pnpm test
   481→```
